<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,458,1281]" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">
The description is brief, but contains more detail than that of the following species. Nevertheless, key characters go unmentioned. Deep red in color, 
<quantity box="[517,595,495,519]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
long, “antennae long, more than 30 segments,” coxal pores “2, 3, 3, 2–4, 5, 5, 5.” 
<bibRefCitation box="[220,536,530,555]" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" refId="ref17312" refString="Williams, S. R. &amp; Hefner, R. A. (1928) The millipedes and centipedes of Ohio. Ohio Biological Survey Bulletin, 4, 91 - 146." type="journal article">Williams and Hefner (1928)</bibRefCitation>
also state: “No pigmented ocelli; a light spot which resembles a non-pigmented area.” Interestingly, the margins of the coxosternum are said to have no teeth. The descriptions by Williams and Hefner of their 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1911" box="[341,467,603,627]" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Buethobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[341,467,603,627]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">Buethobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are accompanied by two crude drawings, labelled only as “ 
<emphasis box="[1287,1436,603,627]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1911" box="[1287,1423,603,627]" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Buethobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Buethobius</taxonomicName>
,”
</emphasis>
without reference to either species. However, 
<figureCitation box="[661,760,638,663]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1114,1136]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1093]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,195,1093]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 26. An unidentified troglomorphic anopsobiid centipede from Lost Soldier Cave, Sequoia Kings Canyon National Park, California. Photograph courtesy of Jean Krejca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455633/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">Fig. 26A</figureCitation>
shows the posterior segments of a female with 5 coxal pores on the 15th coxa, and 
<figureCitation box="[390,489,677,702]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1114,1136]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1093]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[151,1436,195,1093]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 26. An unidentified troglomorphic anopsobiid centipede from Lost Soldier Cave, Sequoia Kings Canyon National Park, California. Photograph courtesy of Jean Krejca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1455633/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">Fig. 26B</figureCitation>
shows a male with a coxal pore formula of 2, 4, 4, 5. Since 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Williams &amp; Hefner" authorityYear="1928" box="[1167,1328,677,701]" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Buethobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="translucens">
<emphasis box="[1167,1328,677,701]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">B. translucens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is said to have coxal pores 2, 2, 2, 2, it seems reasonable to assume that the illustrations are of 
<emphasis box="[1102,1236,713,737]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">
<taxonomicName box="[1102,1232,713,737]" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Buethobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huestoni">B. huestoni</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
However, neither illustration shows the prominent process of the 15th coxa seen in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1911" box="[1009,1135,752,776]" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Buethobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1009,1135,752,776]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">Buethobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. Andrew Weaver collected intensively for many years in 
<collectingRegion box="[595,651,788,813]" country="United States of America" name="Ohio" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">Ohio</collectingRegion>
and never encountered any species of 
<emphasis box="[1088,1221,788,812]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="1911" box="[1088,1217,788,812]" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Buethobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Buethobius</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
though he claimed to have seen one specimen from 
<collectingRegion box="[522,601,824,849]" country="United States of America" name="Illinois" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">Illinois</collectingRegion>
matching the description of 
<taxonomicName box="[925,1052,824,848]" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Buethobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huestoni">
<emphasis box="[925,1052,824,848]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">B. huestoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(A. A. Weaver, unpublished data; this is may be the source of the 
<collectingRegion box="[505,584,860,885]" country="United States of America" name="Illinois" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">Illinois</collectingRegion>
record mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation box="[830,1017,860,885]" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" refId="ref16977" refString="Mercurio, R. J. (2010) An annotated catalog of the centipedes (Chilopoda) from the United States of America, Canada and Greenland (1758 - 2008). XLibris Corporation, Bloomington, IN, 559 pp." type="book chapter">Mercurio [2010]</bibRefCitation>
since Weaver shared his unpublished notes widely), based on the inference that the species lacks coxosternal teeth. However, I found two specimens in the 
<collectionCode box="[196,277,933,957]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">USNM</collectionCode>
collection labelled “ 
<taxonomicName authority="Oxford 1928" authorityName="Oxford" authorityYear="1928" box="[519,917,932,957]" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Buethobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huestoni">Buethobius huestoni Oxford 1928</taxonomicName>
.” On the reverse, the handwritten label says “This is what we called 
<taxonomicName authority="Shear, 2018" authorityName="Shear" authorityYear="2018" box="[433,665,968,993]" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Buethobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huestoni" status="n. sp.">Buethobius huestoni</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[675,737,969,992]" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
we have only 
<specimenCount box="[911,999,968,993]" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" type="male">3 males</specimenCount>
so far.” The specimens, a male and a female, are in poor condition; one complete antenna has 38 segments and the pore counts conform to the range given by 
<bibRefCitation box="[255,555,1040,1065]" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" refId="ref17312" refString="Williams, S. R. &amp; Hefner, R. A. (1928) The millipedes and centipedes of Ohio. Ohio Biological Survey Bulletin, 4, 91 - 146." type="journal article">Williams &amp; Hefner (1928)</bibRefCitation>
. I could not determine with certainty if an ocellus is present, but it appears it is not. As described in 1928, the forcipular coxosterna of both specimens have a straight, even margin lacking teeth. Leg-pairs 1–12 have single-segmented tarsi; the female retains leg 13, which has an incomplete suture dividing the tarsus. Neither specimen has legpairs 14 and 15. The coxae of legpair 15 do not have a distomesal spinous process. This combination of characters is unique in both anopsobiids and henicopids, so determining the status of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shear" authorityYear="2018" class="Chilopoda" family="Henicopidae" genus="Buethobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lithobiomorpha" pageId="11" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huestoni">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">B. huestoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
must wait for fresh collections. Heuston Woods, Oxford, 
<collectingRegion box="[902,961,1220,1245]" country="United States of America" name="Ohio" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">Ohio</collectingRegion>
, the 
<typeStatus box="[1016,1064,1221,1245]" pageId="11" pageNumber="270">type</typeStatus>
locality, is now a protected state park.
</paragraph>
